Explanations of global competitiveness
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Center for International Development at Harvard University published the Global Competitiveness Report (Competitiveness Report) for 2001.
In the study covering 75 countries, Finland, the United States, and Canada occupy the top three places, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe are the laggards.
(All ranking lists can be read at www.weforum.com.)
As a co-leader of this annual study, I am often asked what competitiveness actually means.
Is there a competition both militarily and economically among countries?
Does it even make sense to say that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is precisely defined: namely, as a country's ability to achieve sustainable economic growth in the medium term – that is, over a period of five years.
This definition, however, does not mean that a country's competitiveness also says something about the lack of competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries on Earth could simultaneously achieve higher growth.
It is still sensible to create a ranking of countries in terms of their growth capacity.
Each country is interested in knowing whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep pace with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In some respects, economic growth is comparable to a sporting competition, where the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
Countries compete, for example, for international mobile capital.
The more a country can attract foreign direct investments, the less another country will receive.
It becomes completely clear when countries compete for a specific investment project.
If Intel plans a new semiconductor factory, various countries are invited to submit bids.
The competition for the contract is fierce, and it is often also promoted with tax incentives, infrastructure improvements, and even with adjusted study plans at the local technical university.
This year, we determined a country's competitiveness (growth ability) based on three broad criteria: (1) technology, (2) public institutions, and (3) macroeconomic stability.
For each of these categories, we calculated indicators, whose average values were calculated using a specific method to then create a general growth and competitiveness index.
The technology criterion refers to a country's ability to drive new developments and adopt technologies developed elsewhere.
Some countries like the USA, Japan, Korea, Israel, and Sweden invest heavily in research and development and achieve high innovation values as a result.
Other countries like Argentina and Brazil invest less in research and development and consequently achieve little in terms of new products and processes.
Countries that are innovative enjoy high prosperity due to these innovations.
In this area, the USA, Canada, and Finland occupy the top three places on the ranking list.
The criterion "public institutions" refers to the quality of administration.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts impartial and uncorrupt?
Can one trust that the government will fulfill its obligations properly?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and dysfunctional courts.
High ethical standards promote economic performance.
In this regard, the Nordic European countries are world leaders, and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark are also the top performers on the list.
Corruption is almost unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced national budget, a realistic exchange rate of the national currency, the ability of companies and the government to obtain loans on the capital market, and high trust that the government will fulfill its financial commitments.
We have learned from the example of Asia in the late 1990s that a macroeconomic crisis can wipe out economic growth, even if companies are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries in terms of macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the global economy can be divided into two categories of countries: the innovative and the non-innovative.
Only about 20 countries actively engage in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the richest in the world, a superior system of technological innovation is a prerequisite for continuous competitiveness.
Universities must be excellent, state laboratories should be of world-class quality, and the government and industry should invest heavily in research and development.
A key factor for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who attend higher schools and universities after completing compulsory education.
In the USA and Canada, this proportion is 80%.
For the "non-innovative" countries, technology is equally important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed domestically.
Some countries are good at importing new technologies, while others are less so.
Over the past ten or fifteen years, most technology imports have occurred as part of foreign direct investments.
American companies that invested heavily in Mexico or Taiwanese companies that invested in mainland China also brought in new technologies that increased production efficiency in the target economy.
Therefore, it made sense for the relevant countries to make a strong effort to attract these foreign investments: they bring not only capital, but also new technologies.
A strength and weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is medium-term oriented and does not focus on the next one to two years.
Our rankings are not suitable for evaluating short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they do provide insight into the long-term prospects of major economies.
It is therefore ironic that many of the countries that rank first this year, such as the US or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while others, ranking further down, such as China (rank 39), are not affected by the global recession.
The economic slowdown is partly related to the 9/11 terrorist attacks, but it is also becoming increasingly clear that the US economy and other economies connected to it through trade and production networks were already slipping into recession before September.
However, we believe that this is a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the US will regain its ability to achieve strong economic growth within the next five years.
